                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18490820-1694-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18490820-1694-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18490820-1694-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp>, stealing 1 handkerchief, value 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18490820-name-1138" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18490820-name-1138" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490820-name-1138" type="surname" value="POILE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490820-name-1138" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18490820-1694-offence-1 t18490820-name-1138"></join>Thomas Poile</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18490820-name-1139" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18490820-name-1139" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490820-name-1139" type="surname" value="POILE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490820-name-1139" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS POILE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a pawnbroker. On 28th June I had a conversation with Tarrant, who has pleaded guilty—while I was in conversation with him the prisoner Jacobs came in—I imagine he had heard what had passed between me and Tarrant.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What you said to Jacobs do you think Tarrant had</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184908200170"></xptr>
               <p>heard? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I should think he must—I said to Tarrant, "Where did you get this handkerchief? tell me, or I will send for a constable"—in the early part of that Saturday morning I had found several wrappers, and suspected a robbery—I had not seen Jacobs then when I spoke to Tarrant.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What did Tarrant say upon that observation of yours, and before you saw that Jacobs was in sight? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He said, "I have robbed you of that handkerchief, Sir"—(that was another handkerchief)—and then he said, "Jacobs has robbed you as much as I have"—Jacobs then came from a back warehouse, and said, "You know you are a liar; I have not; I have only robbed you of one silk-handkerchief; "and he took a key from his pocket, and took the handkerchief from his box in the presence of my son, who came up-stairs at that moment.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you asked him any question about Jacobs before? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—after he told me he had robbed me of this handkerchief, and he had said this of Jacobs, he called to Jacobs and said, "Come forward, you have robbed master as well as Í have;" Jacobs said, "You are a liar; I have only taken one handkerchief."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18490820-1694-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
